<font color="#FF0000">MORE ON 31 NUNGS &amp; FAMILIES</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jun 18  2:12:16 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
More on the Nungs.....Exerpts from article in 6/13 Phila. Inquirer, pg 26 by Ted Anthony of Assoc. Press fm Hong Kong:                                                             &quot;Now two decades after the war ended, 31 members of an ethnic group known as the Nung are getting an opportunity, wiht help from their former Special Forces colleagues to leave refugee purgatory in Hong Kong and build new lives with their families in the U.S.&quot;                                                                                        &quot; 'From a Dept. of Defense point of view, each of these persons' claims is valid,' a U.S. official said.  He spoke on condition of anonymity after a week of interviews and evaluations that, by all indications will send the men and their kin - about 180 people - to the U.S. by July 1.&quot;                                                                  &quot;When the North Vietnamese overran South Vietnam in 1975&quot;... &quot;the Nung were left behind in the chaos.  In the 1980's, the Nung joined the exodus of boat people&quot;...&quot;and ended up in a Hong Kong detention center.                                                                                             In April, Special Forces veterans began a campaign of phone calls, letters and email to Congress and the White House.&quot;                                                              &quot;proving the Nung held in Hong Kong were indeed war veterans.  Washington dispatched an investigator.  After a week of interviews, he concluded that each story checked out.  Although they already have been classified as refugees by the U.N., the Nung also must meet the U.S. definition - a similar but entirely separate process that is being expedited because it is 'a rather exceptional circumstance'.&quot;   
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


